    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate with **Yordan Alvarez** (75.76) and **Junior Caminero** (73.34) anchoring our offensive upside. **Yordan Alvarez** benefits from a massive park factor boost (+14%) against Freeland, and despite the L/L disadvantage, his elite xwOBA remains the cornerstone of our lineup. **Junior Caminero** faces the softest opposing arm of the day in Assad (xERA 4.83), making his projected output the most reliable bet for R/RBI production. **Trea Turner** (71.83) and **Kyle Schwarber** (69.61) also grade as elite starts; the wind blowing out in their matchup against Ray provides a meaningful statistical lift to their power ceilings, which is critical given that we are aggressively chasing stolen bases with **Trea Turner** atop the order. **Colt Keith** (67.82) earns a strong start recommendation as well, as his favorable placement at the top of the lineup and the boost from facing Bradley give him a significant edge over his season average.\n\nWhile our top-tier talent is secure, the bottom of the order relies on high-floor utility players. **Victor Scott II** (51.62) and **Carson Benge** (50.97) hover in the marginal-to-strong range; we are prioritizing **Victor Scott II** specifically for his elite sprint speed to protect our standing in the scarce SB category, despite the efficiency drag of hitting 9th. The most difficult roster decision today involved **Jerar Encarnacion**, who was our highest-graded bench piece at 40.21. While he brings power potential, he was squeezed out by the consistency of **Chase Meidroth** (49.47) and the overall depth of our outfield. We remain cautious regarding **Dillon Dingler** (46.59) and **Kazuma Okamoto** (43.82), both of whom are facing difficult SP matchups that threaten their efficiency; however, they remain in the lineup as we prioritize game caps over extreme bench volatility. We are monitoring lineup confirmations for **Trea Turner**, **Yordan Alvarez**, and **Kyle Schwarber** closely, as any shift down the batting order would necessitate a re-evaluation of their daily efficiency scores.",
